268. Missing Number
Given an array nums containing n distinct numbers in the range [0, n], return the only number in the range that is missing from the array.

Example 1:
Input: nums = [3,0,1]
Output: 2
Explanation: n = 3 since there are 3 numbers, so all numbers are in the range [0,3]. 2 is the missing number in the range since it does not appear in nums.

Example 2:
Input: nums = [0,1]
Output: 2
Explanation: n = 2 since there are 2 numbers, so all numbers are in the range [0,2]. 2 is the missing number in the range since it does not appear in nums.

Example 3:
Input: nums = [9,6,4,2,3,5,7,0,1]
Output: 8
Explanation: n = 9 since there are 9 numbers, so all numbers are in the range [0,9]. 8 is the missing number in the range since it does not appear in nums.

 
Constraints:
n == nums.length
1 <= n <= 104
0 <= nums[i] <= n
All the numbers of nums are unique.
 
Follow up: Could you implement a solution using only O(1) extra space complexity and O(n) runtime complexity?

Use Cyclic Sort as number would be given from [0,N]
Logic would search for arr[i] on same index if not return index
If we fully reached the arr.length-1 and not found the missing number then return arr.length

Solution:-
class Solution {
    public void swap(int arr[], int start, int end){
        int temp=arr[start];
        arr[start]=arr[end];
        arr[end]=temp;
    }
    
    public int missingNumber(int[] nums) {
         int i=0;
        while(i< nums.length){
            int crtIndex=nums[i]; //Check for array element is placed in its index or not
            if(nums[i] < nums.length && nums[i] != nums[crtIndex]){
                swap(nums,i,crtIndex); //If array element is not placed in its index then SWAP
            }else{
                i++;
            }
        }
       //Searching for elements
       for(int j=0;j<nums.length;j++){
        if(nums[j] != j){
            return j;
        }
       }
       return (nums.length);
    }
}
